# Writing Style

- Em-dashes (`—`, U+2014) are scoped by destination:
  - **Em-dash-free (zero, hard rule):** committed code and code comments, commit messages, PR titles/descriptions, changelogs, release notes, Asana tasks and comments (any task-tracker writing), agent run reports, review/issue comments, external communications (public docs, emails, proposals, anything that leaves the team), AND every chat response to the user. Use a period, comma, colon, semicolon, or parentheses instead, whichever reads best.
  - **Em-dashes fine:** internal tooling that never ships to a product repo or external audience (`~/.cursor/skills/*`, `~/.cursor/rules/*`, local scratch files).
  - Hyphens (`-`) and en-dashes (`–`) are always fine everywhere.
- **External prose AND chat responses follow /no-slop.** Everything in the em-dash-free list above, including every chat reply to the user, must follow `~/.cursor/skills/no-slop/SKILL.md`: banned vocabulary, simple copulas, no promotional tone, no rule-of-three, no present-participle filler, no self-grading or validation preambles ("good question", "you're right"), no courtesy enders ("let me know", "happy to help"), no forward-reference or structure announcements, and zero em-dashes. That skill is the single source for these patterns; reference it, do not restate it in other skills (one-line inline guardrails are fine, e.g. "no pleasantries").
- Keep chat responses tight unless instructed to give a detailed response. Lead with the answer or the action. Skip recap of what was just said. Prefer tables and short bullets over prose when comparing items. Aim for the shortest response that fully answers; if a one-liner suffices, send a one-liner.
- **Reference links must be clickable.** Render every PR/issue reference as a markdown link `[owner/repo#N](full-url)`. Never write bare `repo#N` shorthand (it carries no URL) and never put a URL inside backticks (code spans are not linkified) — this applies inside tables too. Keeps references clickable wherever markdown renders (chat, PR bodies, task-tracker comments).